("2042","233","_history_tittle_one","field_66c6f81cbce9d"),
("2043","233","history_text_one","The Pan-African Institute of Municipal Development (PIMD) was established in 2020, during the height of the COVID-19 pandemic, to support sustainable municipal governance in African countries through capacity building, leadership development, technical assistance, and knowledge transfer.\r\n\r\nThe Pan-African Institute of Municipal Development (PIMD) was established in 2020, during the height of the COVID-19 pandemic, to support sustainable municipal governance in African countries through capacity building, leadership development, technical assistance, and knowledge transfer.\r\n\r\nPIMD’s Board of Directors combines over 70 years of public sector and local government expertise in U.S. government agencies, including the International Finance Corporation, USAID, MCC, Department of Transportation, the State Department, and the District of Columbia’s Executive Office of the Mayor."),
("2044","233","_history_text_one","field_66c6f82abce9e"),
("2045","233","history_image_two","249"),
("2046","233","_history_image_two","field_66c6f847bce9f"),
("2047","233","history_text_two","Our hands-on approach and practicum research tailored to local challenges provide tools and best practices to meet specific growth objectives. Our programs include robust professional development training curated to promote effective and sustainable municipal leadership. These objectives are achieved through training and research projects specially tailored to target municipalities and strengthen local capacity, develop a competent workforce, and transform municipal employees into powerful partners and allies in the development of the African continent.\r\n\r\nSince our founding in 2020, we have partnered with Yale University to co-design the “How to Tackle Critical Challenges: A Simulation” for the Strategic Impact Leadership Forum hosted at Yale. We have also been invited to participate in the U.S. Africa Leadership Summit hosted by the Biden Administration in 2022 to share our local development and capacity-building model. In addition, PIMD has collaborated closely with the U.S. Embassy in Senegal to implement a Good Governance Practice Program (GGPP) in Guinea-Bissau, designed for civil society members, young professionals, and local government leaders."),
("2048","233","_history_text_two","field_66c6f860bcea0"),
